column33: My community engagement experience impacted my learning about diversity because it taught me that just because someone comes from a marginalized group it does not mean that person will be aware or care for the plight of others oppressed by the same ruling class. I am referring to some members of the staff at SJLI who were part of marginalized communities and cared for them, but when it came to broader social issues, such as the ongoing genocide of Palestinians, they did not find it relevant to their personal struggle for liberation. This deeply inspired me to focus on intersectional education about oppression, liberation, and marginalized communities, because we will not be free until we are all free. We cannot only care about where we come from, even though it is valid for it to be top priority, we must acknowledge that the systems put into place to subjugate one group will always be the same as what is oppressing another, no matter if they seem unrelated.
column34: My community partner, the Social Justice Learning Institute, had me working on their marketing team and health equity team. For marketing, I reached out to company sponsors via email to get swag for their Urban Scholars and made spreadsheets of SJLI's videos in order to use them for their end of school year culmination event and on social media. I also wrote numerous profiles on the Jordan Wings scholarship nominees, SJLI faculty, and family of some of the Urban Scholars. This is all to use on their website and social media to promote their organization and inspire fundraising for the 2024 Urban Scholars Scholarship Fund. On the health equity team, I went to their office in Inglewood on Fridays to help with the weekly food distribution event. This included me helping stuff bags to give to community members, delivering food bags to community members, interviewing volunteers at the food distribution, and loading food into trucks to be distributed.

column5: Little Tokyo Service Center (Mi CASA Afterschool Program) TRACK1
column33: My community engagement experience impacted my learning about diversity because the program was located in downtown LA which has a pretty different demographic and environment than UCLA/ Beverly Hills area. The demographic differs as I saw much more homeless, low income people around Little Tokyo. Additionally, most of the families utilizing the afterschool program lived in the "affordable housing" program provided by the Little Tokyo Service Center. Secondly, the diversity in the environment was very apparent to me as streets became narrower and many more businesses and buildings surrounded/ almost crowded the streets. Overall, my knowledge of diversity expanded after realizing the very different day to day lives everyone lives and the variety of realities that people experience. At first reading the word "diversity," I thought of race, but race was not something that stuck out to me as both the Beverly Hills and downtown parts of LA were made up of people of all races/ ethnicities.
column34: This quarter I contributed to the Little Tokyo Service Center by helping out/volunteering at their Mi CASA afterschool program. There was usually only one or two other staff members, so I think being there, I helped take some kids off of their hands. Especially being in college and still having a lot of energy, I was able to play with multiple kids in the gym and engage in a variety of sport/ active activities with them. I was also able to form meaningful connections with a few of the kids at the program since I would go at the same time and day each week. Not only did I engage in different activities with the kids, but I assisted them with homework and made sure they were safe at all times. Before the kids arrived, I helped set up the room for the program; and, after the kids left, I would help clean up the room and put any books, drawing materials, basketballs, etc.. back to where they belong.

column33: The Cancer Care Institute treats a very diverse range of patients which couldn’t be done without their diverse team. The staff at Cancer Care Institute is very ethnically and curlturally diverse, with hispanic, latino, black, and middle eastern directors, administrators, nurses, etc. running the show. None of this amazing work could be done as successfully without the deep rooted passion of this diverse team. Every single person on the team brings a diverse set of skills and is able to speak their language to each patient, which in this office is predominantly Spanish or Armenian. Having a diverse staff definitely makes the institutions very empathetic towards people from al walks of life, as they handle each patient as their own family. Each staff member contributes to the institution in their unique way by connecting with each patient on a more personal level.
column34: The institute and its volunteers utilize a multitude of non-profit organizations which include over 20 non-profit funds associated with pharmaceutical companies as well as over 50 non-profit organizations that dedicate resources to over 30 different types of cancers. Every patient who is unable to afford their medical care is screened, financially, and if they meet appropriate criteria, they will be matched to as many nonprofit funds to assist them with their financial needs to pay for their cancer care.

column33: My engagement with Rising Communities not only exposed me to the surface-level differences among individuals but also delved into the deeper layers of identity, privilege, and systemic barriers. By actively participating in initiatives aimed at addressing social inequalities and promoting inclusion, I witnessed firsthand the transformative power of community collaboration and education. This experience not only broadened my perspective but also instilled in me a sense of responsibility to advocate for equity and justice in all facets of life. Through meaningful interactions and shared experiences, I came to appreciate diversity not just as a concept, but as a fundamental strength that enriches our collective humanity.

column33: Engaging in sociological imagination allowed me to become familiar with and see societal factors at play in the happenings of our society. Inequalities persist at no fault of the individual and while I've attributed this to the historical context of this country, that I've learned, as an immigrant, much of this same oppressive powers still exists and disrupts liberty by design. It debunks a lot of the myths about moving to America that has been  indoctrinated in us by our immigrant parents that blindly lead us to navigate the factions of American life. Having knowledge about different/diverse groups gives me more perspectives toward where I may find myself in the grand scheme of things and enlighten me about the people that I may have otherwise poorly misjudged.
column34: I was able to set the foundation for the garden in Green Arrow CoLab's community space that would set the stage for the upcoming CESC cohort and young people involved in systemic injustice or that have dealt with incarceration. These community garden spaces are the basis of operation all throughout LA where the direct/downstream solutions take place. By tending the land/soil and planting the first veggies/plants the time spent developing relationships with a group of what we in society considers "other" allowed us to remove stereotypes and gain an understanding of the struggles that also factor in our lives. The realization that regardless of our backgrounds we still face the same issues with the same oppressive powers creates a unity where strategies for change can then be advocated for.

column33: Engaging with the Museum of Social Justice and developing a learning module on social inequality issues in Los Angeles, particularly focusing on water resources, has profoundly impacted my understanding of diversity and its intersection with social justice. Through extensive research and interaction with the museum's exhibitions and resources, I encountered a diverse array of perspectives and experiences related to social inequality. Exploring the different dimensions of inequality also provided insights into how social inequality intertwines with other forms of oppression, such as race, ethnicity, socioeconomic status, and environmental justice. Additionally, engaging with the museum's community-driven approach and attending exhibitions like "Comfort Women" evoked empathy towards marginalized communities and their struggles for justice and equality, empowering me to become a more effective advocate for social change and diversity within my own community.  Overall, this community engagement experience has broadened my understanding of diversity and equipped me with valuable insights and tools to contribute to advocacy efforts for social change and diversity in my community.
column34: During this quarter, I actively collaborated with the Museum of Social Justice to develop a comprehensive learning module addressing social inequality issues in Los Angeles, focusing on water resources. Through thorough research and content creation, I contributed to enhancing the museum's educational resources, empowering community members across age groups to understand and engage with pressing social justice issues. Additionally, I participated in the museum's community-driven initiatives, such as attending the opening day of their newest exhibition, "Comfort Women," and engaging with local voices and stories, amplifying marginalized narratives and fostering empathy within the community. Overall, my contributions this quarter have aimed at enriching educational resources, amplifying marginalized voices, fostering empathy, and promoting awareness and advocacy for social change within the community served by the Museum of Social Justice.

column33: I think having direct conversations with a wide variety of young kids from a variety of different backgrounds gave me a well-rounded view of how the current education system is built. All these kids were smart, funny, talkative, and intuitive yet would remark on wildly different experiences depending on what or where they were schooled. All these conversations exposed me to the fact that the reasons behind educational deficits or surpluses across the city aren't just a race or class or familial or location issue, it's a mixture of all these factors and more. Diversity as a concept shouldn't be a benchmark, it should be a standard.

Through working with BookSustain, I interacted with various communities and organizations, such as shelters and community centers, that serve very diverse populations. This exposure gave me insight to the different socioeconomics backgrounds and challenges faced by individuals in the greater Los Angeles area. BookSustain also made me aware of the educational disparities that exist within my community. I learned about the unequal access to education resources and how this directly affects literacy levels among different demographic groups.
column34: From working with BookSustain, I got to collaborate with them to develop a plan to expand their social impact. Prior to our involvement, BookSustain primarily collected and distributed books to various locations. While this was beneficial, it lacked a clear measure of whether these efforts were effectively achieving their larger goal of expanding literacy. My group and I facilitated connections between BookSustain and charter schools, as well as other volunteer organizations sharing a similar mission to promote literacy. By doing so, we ensured that the donated books were actively used through reading activities, thus contributing to our shared goal. Additionally, we addressed BookSustain's funding challenges by conducting research and presenting them with various methods and strategies to generate revenue. These included innovative approaches such as auctioning off signed books by renowned authors, seeking grants and donations, and exploring avenues like selling books on third-party platforms like Amazon.These are a few of the strategies we presented to BookSustain, and they are likely to have a lasting impact on their operations and the community they serve, promoting access to knowledge and increasing the literacy rate in the Los Angeles area.

column33: Going to Nourish LA left a lasting impact on me, it truly allowed me to interact with what I was learning. I was able to apply what I was learning and have a positive impact on my community, as well as allow me to interact with people from diffrent backgrounds.
column34: I was able to give them valuable feedback, and truly make connections with the community we were helping.

column33: It broadened my perspective on what exactly diversity looks like.
column34: I think just sharing my perspective and experiences and what that looks like.

column33: My community engagement helped me learn that there are so many frames of differences when communicating with others. Everyone has unique experiences and being exposed to this diverse community has really helped broaden my perspectives.
column34: I have been able to help people receive food and be a contributor that process. Engaging with others and helping create a community for beneficiaries and volunteers, even though minute, has been very beneficial to me and the Nourish LA community.

column33: I got to see a different perspective and see how everyone and everything is involved in helping prevent food waste and food insecurity.  I also learned how much food can go straight into landfills and its harmful effects.
column34: I was able to create a newsletter and a handbook for volunteers.

column33: I feel like it didn't impact me in anyway that I wasn't already impacted but it just enhance my drive to create change.
column34: I contributed my time at 826LA to help kids from elementary school to middle school with their writing, homework, and even social skills.

column33: I learned about different frames of difference, this allowed me to understand how everyone starts on a different playing field.
column34: I contributed to this by providing my physical labor, and time and presenting to board members ways they could make it better.

column33: I found it to be a great resource for learning about diversity. By volunteering for this organization I was in constant contact with people from various backgrounds. Our class project required us to think critically about these various differences and how to address everyone with our writing.
column34: I've contributed a lot of time and service to Nourish LA, the community partner. I worked at their site helping pass out food to members of the community. I also made instructional material for this organization to train new volunteers.

column33: It taught me so much about Los Angeles and how diverse this area is. Diversity is very valuable for all aspects of life.
column34: I was the illustrator at the Bookmaking Field Trips. I also helped at the after school writing program.

column33: My community engagement experience impacted my learning about diversity by exposing me to various different people from diverse backgrounds. I was able to interact with different people the days I volunteered at my organization which exposed me to a very diverse community.
column34: I would say I contributed my time and service to my community partner this quarter. I was able to help them in the guests services and help guests and visitors have a positive smooth experience in the CSC.

column33: I was able to see people from different backgrounds, religion, etc. Which also gave me the chance to hear their opinions
column34: I contributed by volunteering and help set up for Nourish LA and gave food for the people in need. I also gave ideas of how Nourish LA can be improved with the group presentations we had to do in class.

column33: my community engagement experience impacted my learning about diversity because I was able to interact and communicate with different students of different backgrounds. Everyone was so diverse and I learned that everyone is capable of completing their work and  have lots of creativity to bring to the class so that they can all create something. They were all different in their own way but they all had it in them to learn, grow and expand.
column34: I contributed a lot of my creativity to this community. First off, I was able to translate for a group of Spanish-speaking kids and in my last session, I was able to illustrate for their book which they all loved. They appreciated my creativity and the fact that the students were able to color their illustrations to make their story better.
